This section details the specific **Technology Stack** and **Core Concepts** used to build the Pallet Ledger Pro.

---

## üõ†Ô∏è The Technology Stack

The project was built using a "Python-First" approach, focusing on rapid development, data integrity, and local portability.

### **1. Frontend & User Interface**

* **[Streamlit](https://streamlit.io/):** Used to build the entire interactive web dashboard. It allows for a clean, responsive UI written entirely in Python, eliminating the need for HTML, CSS, or JavaScript.
* **[Plotly](https://plotly.com/python/):** The engine behind the charts and analytics. It provides interactive visualizations for tracking stock trends and mission volumes.

### **2. Backend & Logic Engine**

* **[Python 3.13+](https://www.python.org/):** The primary programming language used for all business logic, including stock calculations and user role management.
* **[SQLAlchemy (ORM)](https://www.sqlalchemy.org/):** A powerful Object Relational Mapper that lets the app interact with the database using Python objects instead of raw SQL. This ensures the code is readable and maintainable.
* **[Pydantic](https://www.google.com/search?q=https://docs.pydantic.dev/):** Used for strict data validation. It ensures that whenever a location or movement is created, the data (like quantity or mission IDs) follows the correct format before hitting the database.

### **3. Database & Security**

* **[PostgreSQL](https://www.postgresql.org/):** An enterprise-grade relational database used to store all movements, locations, and user data.
* **[Bcrypt](https://pypi.org/project/bcrypt/):** Used for security. It hashes user passwords so they are never stored as plain text, protecting the system from unauthorized access.

### **4. Deployment & Infrastructure**

* **[Docker](https://www.docker.com/):** Containerizes the entire application and database. This ensures the app runs exactly the same on any computer without needing to manually install Python or Postgres.
* **[Docker Compose](https://docs.docker.com/compose/):** Orchestrates the connection between the web app container and the database container automatically.

---

## üß† Core Systems Used

### **The Double-Entry Ledger System**

The most critical part of this project is its **Double-Entry logic**.

* **Every "Movement" is a Transaction:** Just like a bank, you never just "change" a number. You record a movement FROM one base TO another.
* **The Zero-Sum Rule:** If 10 pallets leave Base A, they *must* arrive at Base B or stay in a "Transit" state. This prevents assets from "disappearing" into thin air.

### **Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)**

To maintain security in a military-style environment, the project implements specific roles:

* **Commander:** Full access to add users, decommission bases, and wipe audit logs.
* **Logistics Officer:** Can record movements and view reports but cannot delete locations.
* **Viewer:** Read-only access to view the dashboard and stock levels.

### **Predictive Analytics (Burn Rate)**

The "Advanced Analytics" tab uses a **Burn Rate Engine**. It analyzes the last 30 days of movement history to calculate how fast a base is using its supplies. It then predicts a "Days of Supply" number to warn commanders of imminent stockouts.

